@page "/docs/extensions-whats-next"
@attribute [Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization.Authorize]

@*
    Landing page users are sent to after Generate finishes on
    /projects/new or /projects/extension. The ZIP download is already
    triggered by the time this page loads (the form's response carried
    Content-Disposition: attachment); this page picks up the user where
    the browser's download dialog left them.

    Tone is intentionally soft - many of our users are Business Central
    consultants who do some development but aren't full-time git
    practitioners. Avoid imperative "you must" language; explain the
    why before the what.

    Provider-agnostic by design: we name the popular hosts in passing
    but don't favour one. The generic `git remote add origin <url>`
    pattern works the same way on GitHub, Azure DevOps, GitLab,
    Bitbucket, and self-hosted Gitea.
*@

<PageTitle>What's next · AL Dev Toolbox</PageTitle>

<div class="account-page">
    <header class="page-header">
        <h1>You're all set - here's what's next</h1>
        <p class="muted">
            Your workspace or extension is in your Downloads folder. The rest of
            this page walks through opening it, putting it under source control,
            and pushing it to wherever your team keeps its code. Nothing here is
            mandatory - if you already have a git workflow you like, skip ahead.
        </p>
    </header>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>1. Open the folder</h2>
        <p>
            Unzip the file you just downloaded somewhere you'll find it again -
            most people pick a <code>Projects</code> or <code>Source</code>
            folder under their user directory. The unzipped folder is your
            workspace; everything inside it belongs together.
        </p>
        <p>
            Open that folder in VS Code (<em>File &rarr; Open Folder...</em>) and,
            if it asks, trust the workspace. If VS Code prompts you to install
            the <strong>AL Language</strong> extension, accept - that's the
            Microsoft extension that gives you IntelliSense, compile, and
            launch for Business Central projects.
        </p>
        <p class="muted">
            Two side-cars sit at the workspace root that you don't need to
            touch: a <code>.code-workspace</code> file (VS Code reads it to
            know which folders belong together) and a
            <code>workspace.aldt.toml</code> file (AL Dev Toolbox uses it if
            you ever come back to regenerate the workspace). Leave them where
            they are - they travel with the project.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>2. Save it with git</h2>
        <p>
            Git is the safety net that records every change you make so you
            can roll back when something breaks, see who changed what, and
            share your work with teammates. The workspace already has a
            <code>.gitignore</code> in it, so git knows to skip the build
            output and other generated files.
        </p>
        <p>
            Open a terminal inside the workspace folder (in VS Code:
            <em>Terminal &rarr; New Terminal</em>) and run these three
            commands. They tell git to start tracking the folder, stage all
            the files you just got, and record the first snapshot.
        </p>
        <pre><code>git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial workspace from AL Dev Toolbox"</code></pre>
        <p class="muted">
            If git complains that it doesn't know who you are, it'll tell you
            exactly which two commands to run to set your name and email - a
            one-time setup per machine. Paste those, then re-run
            <code>git commit</code>.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>3. Push it to your team's host</h2>
        <p>
            "Push" means uploading your local history to a server so other
            people can see it and so your work survives if your laptop
            disappears. The server is usually one of:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>GitHub</strong> - common for open source and many product teams.</li>
            <li><strong>Azure DevOps</strong> - common for Microsoft-stack consultancies and enterprises.</li>
            <li><strong>GitLab</strong>, <strong>Bitbucket</strong>, <strong>Gitea</strong>, or your own self-hosted server - the underlying git is the same.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Each provider has its own UI for creating a new repository, but the
            steps are roughly the same: sign in, click <em>New repository</em>
            (or <em>New repo</em>), give it a name, and leave the "initialize
            with README" boxes unchecked - your local folder is already
            initialised, so an empty remote is what you want.
        </p>
        <p>
            Once it's created, the provider shows you a URL that looks
            something like one of these:
        </p>
        <pre><code>https://github.com/your-org/customer-cronus.git
https://dev.azure.com/your-org/your-project/_git/customer-cronus
git@gitlab.com:your-org/customer-cronus.git</code></pre>
        <p>
            Copy whichever URL your provider shows. Back in your terminal,
            point your local repository at it and push the first commit:
        </p>
        <pre><code>git remote add origin &lt;paste the URL here&gt;
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main</code></pre>
        <p class="muted">
            That second line renames your local branch to <code>main</code>
            so it lines up with what most hosts expect by default. If you'd
            rather use <code>master</code>, <code>trunk</code>, or anything
            else, swap it in - git doesn't care. The <code>-u</code> in the
            push command tells git "remember this remote next time", so from
            then on a plain <code>git push</code> works.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>From here on</h2>
        <p>
            Day-to-day, the loop is small: edit files, save, then run
            <code>git add</code> / <code>git commit</code> / <code>git push</code>
            when you've finished something worth saving. VS Code's
            <strong>Source Control</strong> pane (the branch icon in the
            sidebar) gives you buttons for all of that if you'd rather not
            type the commands.
        </p>
        <p>
            If you need another extension on top of this workspace later,
            head back to <a href="/projects/extension">New extension</a> -
            pick the same template and AL Dev Toolbox will add a sibling
            folder alongside the ones you already have.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>Stuck?</h2>
        <p>
            None of the commands above will destroy work you haven't pushed
            yet. If something looks wrong, take a breath; the original ZIP
            is still in your Downloads folder, and a fresh
            <a href="/projects/new">New workspace</a> is always one click
            away. For team-specific things - which host to use, what the
            repo should be named, who owns what - your tech lead or
            architect is the right person to ask.
        </p>
    </section>
</div>
